00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:12.640
Thank you. One that just came in is, what are some alternative approaches that you have seen customers use when retrieving user-specific data from an external data catalog?

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:19.640
Yeah, it's a good question.

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:34.640
I think the most common one we've seen, like specifically within the context of Connect, is deploying those multiple instances of the same app

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:51.640
and setting static service account-esque credentials on that app, where the service account has the same permissions as the user that is interacting with that duplicated instance of the app that's published,

00:19:51.640 --> 00:20:00.640
which obviously is very clunky, and that's why we wanted to build this feature.

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:09.640
That's the main one that I'm aware of that people have used as alternative approaches to try to do this type of workflow.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:16.640
I don't know if David or Pablo are aware of any other things, but that's the main one that I know of.

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:23.640
There are two others that come to mind.

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:29.640
There's the possibility of actually implementing OAuth inside of your content.

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:40.640
It is technically possible to handle the OAuth flow from your content, but it would mean you would have to implement it for every piece of content, and that's a lot of work.

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:47.640
It's also really difficult to maintain, and it gets really complicated, particularly with high-availability Connect.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:54.640
You never know which Python or R process you're going to connect to, and so that would be weird.

00:20:54.640 --> 00:21:03.640
The other option is using some of the metadata provided by Connect when the content is running.

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:10.640
Connect does expose information about the connecting viewer to the content itself.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:13.640
You can get that information out of one of Connect's headers.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:18.640
You could write application-specific logic for every piece of content that says,

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:26.640
if this viewer then access the external resource with this other set of credentials, but that doesn't scale very well either.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:36.640
So we think that what we've got here is a much better approach for managing that because it's going to scale a little bit better.

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:43.640
Rather than maintaining that access control logic inside of your content,

00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:53.640
you can maintain the access control logic at the data source where they have really robust controls for writing those access control rules.

00:21:57.640 --> 00:21:59.640
Thank you.

