00:23:25.640 --> 00:23:33.640
Yes, for sure.

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:43.640
There's a lot of different ways that you could think about this question and what the security considerations are.

00:23:43.640 --> 00:23:51.640
We have a doc in our admin guide that lays out a lot of those implications.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:24:06.640
The sort of high-level summary I can give here is that publishers and app writers need to consider sort of the lifecycle of their app

00:24:06.640 --> 00:24:14.640
and where in memory the OAuth credentials are and avoid using, for example, global variables to store that information.

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:20.640
But we have a doc that helps kind of talk through what those security considerations are

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:24.640
and the things to be aware of when writing your apps.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:35.640
But the publishers just need to be aware of how the feature works and where those credentials are stored.

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:39.640
That's the main thing to be aware of when using the feature.

