I'm very hesitant to bring it up at all.

00:26:42.640 --> 00:26:50.640
But I do want to point out that this feature is similar to run as current user,

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:53.640
but it is still a little bit different.

00:26:55.640 --> 00:27:00.640
Run as current user allows the viewer of an application to view the application.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:05.640
Basically, it's a way to use Kerberos with Connect.

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.640
But it does require PAM authentication.

00:27:08.640 --> 00:27:12.640
And this new feature can be used with any authentication provider.

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:14.640
So that's one distinction.

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:18.640
Another distinction is that with run as current user,

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:23.640
every viewer of the application is executing the copy of the application.

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:26.640
Another distinction is that with run as current user,

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:35.640
every viewer of the application is executing the content in their own isolated process on the server.

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:39.640
This OAuth integrations feature will share content processes under the hood.

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:44.640
So every viewer of the application is not getting their own instance of a process.

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:46.640
It does have some different security implications.

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:51.640
We try to talk about that a little bit in the security talk that we've already shared out in the chat.

00:27:51.640 --> 00:27:54.640
But this new feature is much more lightweight.

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:57.640
And it's going to work with any authentication provider.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:27:59.640
Those are the main distinctions.

